{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536572"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:08:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:08:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15804"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15804"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.21,0.13,0.47,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8495"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62658"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8495"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15804"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48106"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1519"},{"type":"tags","id":"3516"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5066"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20409"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62658"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe general medical intern is asked to review a 78-year-old patient on the medical ward for a new finding of sodium 152 mmol/L (135-145). She was admitted three days ago for treatment of community-acquired pneumonia. She has a history of congestive cardiac failure, type 2 diabetes and short-term memory loss. Her regular medications are metformin, furosemide, ramipril, and spironolactone. In addition, she is receiving intravenous ceftriaxone and azithromycin for treatment of her pneumonia. She has never smoked and only drinks alcohol socially. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears mildly confused but otherwise well. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. She has dry mucous membranes and reduced skin turgor. Her jugular venous pressure is not elevated and she has mild ankle oedema.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications is most likely contributing to her hypernatraemia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Metformin","Spironolactone","Ramipril","Furosemide","Ceftriaxone"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with hypernatraemia and clinical signs of dehydration while taking multiple medications that can affect fluid and electrolyte balance. Understanding the mechanisms of action of these medications is crucial for identifying the likely cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFurosemide\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely contributor to this patient\u0027s hypernatraemia. As a loop diuretic, it causes excessive free water loss through inhibition of the sodium-potassium-chloride cotransporter in the ascending loop of Henle. This interferes with the kidney\u0027s ability to concentrate urine, leading to disproportionate free water loss compared to sodium, particularly if fluid intake is inadequate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetformin\u003C/strong\u003E does not directly affect sodium balance. While it can cause gastrointestinal side effects that might contribute to dehydration, it is not typically associated with hypernatraemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERamipril\u003C/strong\u003E, an ACE inhibitor, typically has no direct effect on sodium levels. In fact, it can occasionally cause hyponatraemia through its effects on aldosterone suppression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpironolactone\u003C/strong\u003E, a potassium-sparing diuretic, acts by blocking aldosterone receptors. While it has diuretic effects, it is not typically associated with hypernatraemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECeftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E does not typically cause significant changes in sodium levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of this patient should include careful review of fluid status, adjustment of diuretic dosing, and ensuring adequate fluid intake. The underlying pneumonia may also be contributing to fluid losses through fever and tachypnoea, though these are not currently present.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Loop diuretics can cause hypernatraemia through free water loss and sodium retention","Careful medication review is essential in investigating electrolyte disturbances","Common medications that can contribute to hypernatraemia include diuretics, lactulose, and lithium"],"references":["Sonani B, Naganathan S, Al-Dhahir MA. Hypernatremia. [Updated 2023 Aug 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441960/","Liamis G, Filippatos TD, Elisaf MS. Evaluation and treatment of hypernatremia: a practical guide for physicians. Postgrad Med. 2016;128(3):299-306. doi: 10.1080/00325481.2016.1147322. Epub 2016 Feb 23. PMID: 26813151."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48106"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15804"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48106","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48106"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-18T09:29:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-18T09:30:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8495"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62658"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1172","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1172"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"EUC","synonyms":["Electrolytes urea creatinine","UEC","Renal function tests","RFTs","Urea/electrolytes/creatinine","Electrolytes/urea/creatinine","Biochemistry"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-07-28T11:34:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-11T10:56:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"t